  <!-- TYPES OF RADIATOR -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f1f5f9;">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Types of Radiator We Supply and Fit in Liverpool</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">We supply and fit every type of radiator found in Liverpool homes, from standard panel radiators to period column styles.</p>

      <div class="pf-who-grid" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-who-item pf-who-yes"><span class="pf-who-icon">✓</span><div><strong>Standard panel radiators</strong><p>Single and double panel radiators are the most common type found across Liverpool. Double convector (type 22) radiators deliver the highest heat output for their size and are our standard recommendation for most Liverpool rooms. Available in all standard lengths and heights.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-who-item pf-who-yes"><span class="pf-who-icon">✓</span><div><strong>Column radiators</strong><p>Traditional column radiators are popular in Liverpool's Victorian and Edwardian properties where period aesthetics matter. We supply steel column radiators in two, three and four column configurations, available in heights from 600mm to 1800mm. Correct sizing is critical. We calculate the output needed for the room before recommending a model.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-who-item pf-who-yes"><span class="pf-who-icon">✓</span><div><strong>Designer and flat panel radiators</strong><p>Vertical designer radiators are a good solution for rooms where horizontal wall space is limited. We fit designer radiators in all standard sizes and advise on output requirements before supply. Note that designer radiators with low surface area can underperform in larger Liverpool rooms if not correctly sized.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-who-item pf-who-yes"><span class="pf-who-icon">✓</span><div><strong>Bathroom and towel radiators</strong><p>Heated towel rails and bathroom radiators are available in chrome, white and anthracite finishes. We can connect these to your central heating circuit or install a dual fuel version that works independently from the main heating system. Useful in Liverpool properties where the bathroom is not always heated with the rest of the house.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-who-item pf-who-yes"><span class="pf-who-icon">✓</span><div><strong>Underfloor heating coexistence</strong><p>If your Liverpool property has underfloor heating in some rooms and radiators in others, we can extend the radiator circuit into rooms the underfloor system does not reach. This is common in Liverpool extensions and kitchen renovations where underfloor was fitted but the rest of the house uses radiators.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-who-item pf-who-yes"><span class="pf-who-icon">✓</span><div><strong>Low surface temperature radiators</strong><p>Low surface temperature (LST) radiators are required in care settings and recommended in rooms used by young children or vulnerable adults. The radiator surface stays below 43 degrees regardless of the water temperature. We supply and fit LST radiators to any Liverpool property where they are required.</p></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SIGNS RADIATORS NEED ATTENTION -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Signs Your Liverpool Radiators Need Attention</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">These are the most common radiator problems we attend across Liverpool. Most are straightforward to diagnose and resolve.</p>

      <div class="pf-signs" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Cold at the bottom, warm at the top</strong><p>Sludge and magnetite build-up settles at the bottom of the radiator and blocks heat circulation. Bleeding will not resolve this. A power flush is the correct treatment. If multiple radiators in your Liverpool home have cold bottoms, the whole system needs flushing.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Cold at the top, warm at the bottom</strong><p>Air in the system rises to the top of the radiator and displaces water. Bleeding with a radiator key resolves this. If the radiator repeatedly needs bleeding, there is air entering the system which needs investigation, usually a failing pump seal or a small leak in the circuit.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Radiator completely cold</strong><p>A fully cold radiator on an otherwise working system usually indicates a stuck thermostatic valve or a blockage in the radiator itself. We can diagnose this on a visit and often resolve it on the same call without replacing the radiator.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Radiator leaking at valve or connection</strong><p>A small drip from a valve or pipe connection can usually be stopped by tightening the gland nut or replacing the valve insert. Left unattended, a leaking radiator can cause significant water damage to flooring and ceilings in Liverpool's multi-floor properties.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Radiator making noise</strong><p>Ticking when the heating comes on is normal thermal expansion. Persistent banging, gurgling or whistling indicates air in the system, sludge circulation or pump problems. We diagnose the cause before recommending any work.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Radiator visibly corroded or damaged</strong><p>Surface rust on an older radiator accelerates internal corrosion. A radiator with visible through-corrosion or physical damage should be replaced rather than repaired. A corroding radiator also releases iron oxide into the system, accelerating sludge build-up throughout the circuit.</p></div></div>
      </div>

